The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Thursday, January 22, 2004 				 Southern solace for chronic ailments
 A STAFF REPORTER																								From musculo-skeletal disorders to neurological problems to chronic respiratory diseases  Kerala ayurveda offers treatment for a wide range of ailments. And Calcuttans can avail of free medical consultation with doctors attached to the Arya Vaidya Pharmacy (Coimbatore) Ltd, one of the pioneers in modern Indias ayurveda revival, over the next six days at the South Indian Festival at Swabhumi (January 22-27).																								The festival, which will also showcase art and culture, handicrafts and cuisine of the southern states, has laid great stress on ayurvedic medicinal solutions from down South. Arya Vaidya Pharmacy will offer its holistic system of ayurveda treatments and medicines  both restorative and rejuvenating  at the festival. Ayurveda uses palliative and eliminative measures to modulate body and mind to preserve good health, explains K.S. Namboodri a physician with the organisation.																								According to the festival organisers, Arya Vaidya Pharmacy is engaged in manufacturing and marketing ayurvedic medicines, research, treatment, education, bio-diversity conservation and other related areas. Being a holistic system, ayurveda treatments and medicines are patient-specific and adaptable to ones living conditions and, therefore, extremely relevant in todays context, says Namboodri.																								He and his colleagues will offer special Kerala ayurveda treatments for common problems like rheumatoid arthritis, back pain, lumbar spondylosis, neurological complaints like hermiplegia and facial paralysis, besides allergy, asthma and migraine.																								Apart from seeking southern comfort for chronic ailments, one can also pick up an Ikkat or a Narayanpet sari, a Tanjore painting or some silver filigree at the festival. Gourmets can gorge on fish and tapioca, Malabar paratha or Hyderabadi biryani. For the culturally inclined, there will be recitals of Kathakali and Mohiniattam, besides folk performances and street theatre.
